<HEADLINE>
<P>
CONSUMER BRIEFS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Maybe It's the Long Lines: When it comes to dealing with the public, grocery 
checkout clerks were rated the least helpful or friendly, according to a survey 
of 1,312 consumers by marketing consultant Wunderman Cato Johnson, part of the 
advertising agency Young & Rubicam. Airline check-in employees were the 
second-most annoying, flight attendants were third and airline phone personnel 
were fifth.The No. 4 spot went to hotel check-in clerks. Department store 
salespeople ranked sixth on the list of least effective, bank officers ranked 
seventh, bank tellers eighth, cable TV phone personnel ninth and rental car 
phone personnel 10th. The employees rated most helpful and friendly included 
credit card phone representatives, at No. 1, followed by rental car desk clerks 
and long-distance phone personnel. 
</P>
