<HEADLINE>
<P>
GEPHARDT GALLBLADDER IS REMOVED IN SURGERY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Rep. Richard A. Gephardt (D-Mo.) underwent surgery to remove his gallbladder 
Thursday, a day after he was chosen by fellow House Democrats as minority 
leader when the new Congress convenes in January. 
</P>
<P>
 A statement from Gephardt's office said that the congressman was "resting 
comfortably" after the surgery and that he was expected to remain at Bethesda 
Naval Hospital until the weekend. "A full recovery is expected," the statement 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 The 53-year-old lawmaker had first suffered abdominal pains on Tuesday and 
tests revealed the presence of gallstones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
