<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS FOCUS: HUNTINGTON BEACH; JOLLY TYPES SOUGHT TO BE SANTAS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DEBRA CANO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Finding a jolly, fat and white-bearded man to play the role of St. Nick is not 
easy, according to Kim Wood. 
</P>
<P>
 "They have to enjoy working with kids, and they have to be able to convince 
kids they are Santa," said Wood, coordinator for the city's Rent-A-Santa 
program. 
</P>
<P>
 Wood is holding auditions in search of Santas to participate in the 
Rent-A-Santa program. Santa visits will be available from Dec. 9 to 23. Visits 
will be scheduled Wednesdays through Sundays. 
</P>
<P>
 Wood said that those selected must not only look and act the part but also be 
punctual, be in good health and pass a security background check. 
</P>
<P>
 Those chosen to play the role of Santa Claus will make 15-minute visits to 
homes and may make special appearances. 
</P>
<P>
 The popular program faced cancellation this Christmas season -- a casualty of 
the city's budget woes. But after an outcry by residents wanting the 
Rent-A-Santa program, the city relented. 
</P>
<P>
 "We had a lot of complaints. People were upset," Wood said. 
</P>
<P>
 Santas get paid $7.32 per 15-minute visit. Santa's elves -- people who will 
drive Santa to his visits -- are also needed. Elves get paid $7.32 an hour. The 
city will provide the costumes. 
</P>
<P>
 The cost for Santa visits is $15 for a 15-minute visit with as many as five 
children. Visits will be scheduled between 3 and 9 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
 Those interested in playing Santa or an elf or residents wanting to schedule a 
visit can call (714) 536-5486. The deadline to submit a Santa application is 
Wednesday.DEBRA CANO 
</P>
</TEXT>
