<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS FOCUS: COSTA MESA; OCC FACULTY TO HOST HUMAN RIGHTS PANEL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALICIA DI RADO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Faculty members at Orange Coast College will host a conference on human rights 
next week. 
</P>
<P>
 The college's International Education Committee -- which encourages teaching 
students about their place in a global community -- will put on "Human Rights 
Day of the United Nations" panels Thursday, OCC Assistant Prof. Fazlollah 
Berdjis said. 
</P>
<P>
 Speakers will talk about how the United Nations can work to prevent oppression 
worldwide and are likely to discuss civil war in the former Yugoslavia, Berdjis 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 Tamy Jacobi, deputy director of the Western region of Amnesty International, 
will give a report on human rights violations across the world, said Berdjis. 
</P>
<P>
 Other speakers scheduled to appear include: Cal State Fullerton Prof. Roger 
Dittmann, a nuclear physicist and chair of the Los Angeles chapter of the 
Federation of American Scientists; Kurt Bergel, co-director of the Albert 
Schweitzer Institute at Chapman University, and James F. Nelson, former 
presiding judge of the Los Angeles Municipal Court and chairman of the National 
Spiritual Assembly of the Baha'is of the United States. 
</P>
<P>
 The free conference will be from 7:30 to 10 p.m. in Room 119 of OCC's Fine 
Arts Building. For more information, call (714) 556-6509.ALICIA DI RADO 
</P>
</TEXT>
