community were protest rallies and soliciting victims of Muldrew who live 
within 35 miles of Covina. Under state law, parolees cannot be released within 
35 miles of his victims or those who testified against them in court. 
</P>
<P>
 In the Antelope Valley, about 40 residents who had gathered Thursday afternoon 
at Lancaster City Park to protest Muldrew's release applauded loudly when 
organizers announced that he would remain in prison. 
</P>
<P>
 The rally was organized after Muldrew was transferred to the state prison in 
Lancaster for his pre-parole psychiatric evaluation, and a television news 
report suggested that if he passed, Muldrew could be released in one of the 
surrounding communities. 
</P>
<P>
 Alma Hasse, a Palmdale resident who has two daughters, ages 12 and 14, joined 
a local radio station, KLKX-FM, in organizing Thursday's rally. Participants 
signed petitions and form letters urging Gov. Pete Wilson to press for laws 
requiring wider community notification when a violent criminal is released in 
the area. 
</P>
<P>
 "In the short term, I am ecstatic," Hasse said upon learning that Muldrew will 
remain behind bars, at least temporarily. "In the long run, I hope the laws 
regarding parole notification will be changed." 
</P>
<P>
 Lancaster City Councilman George Runner said some might regard the rally as an 
overreaction because state officials never said publicly that they were 
considering releasing Muldrew in the Antelope Valley. But he said residents 
were angry because corrections officials never ruled out the Antelope Valley, 
either. 
</P>
<P>
 Art Lucero, deputy regional parole administrator, said the state decided to 
perform the psychiatric evaluation partly because of the extreme violence 
involved in the crimes for which Muldrew was convicted. He at times beat and 
punched his victims, or put out cigarettes on their skin. 
</P>
<P>
 Lucero said he was not sure whether Muldrew had a history of mental illness 
before his crimes. 
</P>
<P>
